1. PLANNING AND CONCEPT

Game Idea: Define the core concept and gameplay mechanics (e.g., platformer, shooter, RPG). Include a market analysis to understand the niche your game targets and how it differentiates itself. (Team members: Game Designer, Market Analyst)
Art Direction: Decide on the style (e.g., 2D pixel art, 3D realistic, cartoonish). Create a visual style guide for consistency in colors, fonts, and overall design. (Team members: Art Director, Visual Designer)
Target Platform: Determine whether the game is for mobile, desktop, or web. Consider the technical requirements for each platform (e.g., performance constraints for mobile, system specs for PC). (Team members: Technical Lead, Platform Specialist)
Budget and Timeline: Estimate the time and resources needed. Add a risk management section outlining potential risks and contingencies (e.g., delays, technical issues). (Team members: Project Manager, Lead Developer)
Team Roles: Assign roles (e.g., programmer, artist, sound designer). Include sub-roles (e.g., environmental artist, narrative designer) for clearer responsibilities. (Team members: Project Manager)

2. PROJECT SETUP

Create a New Project: Start with the latest version of Godot (in this case, 4.6). (Team members: Lead Developer)
Set Up Directories: Create the following main directories in your project folder:
scenes/ for game scenes
scripts/ for GDScript files
assets/ for images, sound files, fonts, etc.
shaders/ for custom shaders
ui/ for user interface elements
prefabs/ for reusable game objects
localization/ for future internationalization
docs/ for project documentation
(Team members: Lead Developer, Technical Artist)
Version Control (Git): Set up a Git repository to track changes, backups, and collaboration. Use gitignore to avoid tracking unnecessary files (e.g., cache files, compiled code, temporary files). (Team members: Technical Lead, Developer)

3. GAME DESIGN DOCUMENT (GDD)

Game Mechanics: Describe the rules, goals, win/loss conditions, and game loops (e.g., exploration, combat, puzzle-solving). (Team members: Game Designer, Lead Developer)
Storyline, Characters, and World-Building: Include a section for player progression (leveling, skill acquisition, inventory systems). (Team members: Narrative Designer, Game Designer)
Controls, HUD, and UI Elements: Add wireframe mockups to visualize the layout and transitions between menus and scenes. (Team members: UI/UX Designer, Game Designer)
Level Design and Progression: Plan level structure and progression (e.g., difficulty curve, unlockable areas). (Team members: Level Designer, Game Designer)
Audio Design: Define the sound mood for each scene and character. Consider a "musical identity" or key instruments/genres. (Team members: Sound Designer, Composer)

4. PROTOTYPE AND PROOF OF CONCEPT

Build a Simple Prototype: Start by implementing basic gameplay mechanics, movement, or core interactions.
Prototype 1: Character movement and basic interactions.
Prototype 2: Core mechanics, combat, or level design.
(Team members: Lead Developer, Programmer)
Playtesting: Test the core gameplay and adjust it based on feedback. Incorporate player feedback tools (e.g., surveys, user testing). (Team members: QA Tester, Lead Developer)

5. SCENE AND ASSET DESIGN

Create Scenes: Build different scenes for your game (e.g., Menu, Game, Game Over). Break each scene into different nodes like:
Control Nodes for UI (buttons, sliders, etc.)
Sprite Nodes for visuals
Collision Nodes for interactions
MeshInstance3D for 3D objects
(Team members: Scene Designer, Programmer)
Assets:
Use Sprite nodes for 2D assets (e.g., characters, backgrounds).
Create AudioStreamPlayer nodes for sound effects and background music.
Specify asset formats (e.g., 2048x2048 for backgrounds, 64x64 for icons).
(Team members: 2D Artist, 3D Artist, Sound Designer)
Shaders: Create custom shaders for visual effects (e.g., lighting, reflections, stylized effects). (Team members: Technical Artist, Shader Developer)

6. PROGRAMMING AND GAMEPLAY MECHANICS

Player Controls: Set up character movement, physics, and animations using GDScript or C#. Ensure proper feedback (e.g., visual/audio cues when the player hits obstacles). (Team members: Programmer, Animator)
Input Handling: Use Godot’s input system (e.g., arrow keys, WASD). (Team members: Programmer)
Collision Detection: Set up collision shapes with KinematicBody2D/3D for player movement. (Team members: Programmer)
AI: Add enemy behaviors and interactions (e.g., pathfinding, state machines). Consider adaptive AI for difficulty adjustments. (Team members: AI Programmer)
Game Loop: Define how the game runs by managing:
Game states (main menu, in-game, pause, game over)
Level progression
Score tracking
(Team members: Lead Developer, Programmer)
Shaders: Create custom visual effects like lighting, reflections, or stylized effects for enhanced gameplay visuals. (Team members: Shader Developer, Visual Designer)

7. UI AND MENUS

UI Design: Implement a clean and intuitive interface (e.g., start menu, options, score display). Add user testing to ensure intuitiveness. (Team members: UI/UX Designer)
Signals and Events: Use Godot’s signals to manage interactions between UI elements.
Button Press → Change scene (start game)
Score Update → Display new score in UI
(Team members: Programmer, UI/UX Designer)
Responsive UI: Ensure that the UI scales properly on different screen sizes using Control nodes and anchoring. (Team members: UI/UX Designer)

8. SOUND AND MUSIC

Background Music: Loop background music using AudioStreamPlayer. (Team members: Composer, Sound Designer)
Sound Effects: Use AudioStreamPlayer for effects like jumping, shooting, and collisions. (Team members: Sound Designer)
Audio Management: Handle volume control for music and sound effects in the settings menu. (Team members: Sound Designer)

9. OPTIMIZATION

Memory Management: Be mindful of memory usage; optimize assets (e.g., compress textures). Use tools like Valgrind or Godot’s profiler for memory leak detection. (Team members: Lead Developer, Technical Artist)
Performance: Optimize performance (FPS stability) by reducing unnecessary computations and optimizing physics. Profile the game regularly to detect slowdowns. (Team members: Programmer, Technical Lead)
Profiling: Use Godot’s built-in profiler to track performance bottlenecks. (Team members: Programmer, Lead Developer)

10. TESTING AND DEBUGGING

Playtesting: Test the game regularly and adjust the difficulty curve, balance, and mechanics based on feedback. Focus on player experience across different player types (casual, expert). (Team members: QA Tester, Lead Developer)
Debugging: Use Godot’s debugger to track issues (e.g., errors, logic bugs). Consider automated testing for key gameplay mechanics. (Team members: Programmer, Lead Developer)
QA: If working with a team, have others test the game for bugs or gameplay issues. (Team members: QA Tester)

11. POLISHING

Graphics: Finalize art, animations, and visual effects. Ensure smooth game feel (e.g., responsive controls, polished animations). (Team members: 2D Artist, Animator, Visual Designer)
Audio: Polish sound effects, music, and voice acting. (Team members: Composer, Sound Designer)
UI/UX: Ensure that the user interface is polished and responsive across devices and resolutions. (Team members: UI/UX Designer)

12. RELEASE AND DISTRIBUTION

Build: Build the game for the target platform (PC, mobile, web). Follow platform-specific guidelines for export (e.g., Android/PC export settings). (Team members: Lead Developer, Programmer)
Store Setup: Prepare the game for release on platforms like Steam, Google Play, or Itch.io. (Team members: Project Manager, Marketing Specialist)
Marketing: Create promotional material (e.g., trailers, screenshots) and develop a marketing plan to build community engagement (e.g., Discord, social media). (Team members: Marketing Specialist)

13. POST-LAUNCH UPDATES

Bug Fixes: Address player-reported issues post-launch. (Team members: Programmer, Lead Developer)
Content Updates: Plan and release new features, levels, or events to keep players engaged. Add seasonal updates or DLC content to retain interest. (Team members: Game Designer, Programmer)
